<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   2 June 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> GUATEMALA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bombs Rock Capital Prior To Resumption of Peace Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bombs Rock Capital Prior To Resumption of Peace Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Army Spokeswoman Blames URNG </H4>

<F P=102> PA0306043494 Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 2 Jun 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PA0306043494 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Army spokeswoman Edith Vargas de Marroquin has 
blamed the Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity (URNG) for 
last night's bomb attacks against a shopping mall and the 
residence of Fernando Quezada Toruno. 
  The Army spokeswoman has said the guerrillas are the only 
ones capable of placing such bombs, which endanger the lives of 
the people, as what happened the night of 31 May when they 
exploded in the urban sector. 
  The explosions caused damage to Climat, a boutique located 
at 
No. 13-70 7th Avenue, Zone 9, and the residence of lawyer 
Fernando Quezada Toruno, the brother of Monsignor Rodolfo 
Quezada Toruno, president of the Civil Sectors Assembly. 
  The URNG could be responsible for the two bombs at the two 
locations, Government Minister Danilo Parrinello Blanco said 
yesterday. 
  We knew of a terrorist escalation, but we cannot ascertain 
the guerrillas are responsible for the bomb explosions, 
although, by logic, we can surmise they did it, the minister 
said. 
  There is no other reason to think this was an action by 
another group, but the investigations underway will confirm it, 
Parrinello Blanco concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

