<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TOT-94-023-L </AU>
JPRS 
Terrorism 

</HEADER>

<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   28 May 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> RUSSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Carbomb Kills Chechen Minister, Wounds President </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Carbomb Kills Chechen Minister, Wounds President </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    President Dudayev Survives </H4>

<F P=102> LD2805132394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1115 
GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2805132394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Ostanin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 28 May -- An attempt was made on the life of 
Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev on 27 May. An ITAR-TASS 
correspondent learned this from Chechnya's press and information 
ministry today. 
  The attempt occurred at 1900 hours along the road to Groznyy 
when the motorcade in which the president was travelling passed 
a Lada car parked on the side of the road. The blast from the 
powerful car bomb killed Interior Minister Magomet Eldiyev, his 
deputy Saidali Batayev, and the driver of their car, who were 
accompanying the president. The car in which the Chechen 
president was riding was thrown 10 meters by the explosion, but 
the president was not hurt. 
  ITAR-TASS learned from Shirlai Pashayev, Chechnya's deputy 
minister for information and the press, that components of a 
remote control triggering device were found at the scene of the 
attempt. According to Pashayev, similar devices have not been 
used before on the territory of the Chechen Republic. An 
investigation is under way. 
  A decision was adopted at an emergency sitting of the 
Chechen 
cabinet of ministers today to declare Sunday, 29 May, a day of 
mourning. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

