<H4>    Groznyy Blames Russian Government </H4>

<F P=102> LD3005145194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1252 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3005145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Chechen leaders accused Moscow of elevating 
terrorism to the level of state policy, but stated that "under 
no circumstance will they resort to return measures." On 
Monday, the Chechen Foreign Ministry circulated a statement 
which lays the blame for such a policy on the Russian 
authorities. 
  The attempt on the life of President Dudayev on May 27 was 
merely the latest terrorist act carried out by the Russian 
special services over the three years since the Chechen state 
came into existence, says the statement. [passage omitted] 
  "Under the cover of democratic rhetoric, the Russian 
leadership is undermining the sovereignty of Chechnya," says 
this document. "All this is taking place amid reports about 
forthcoming talks between Boris Yeltsin and Dzhokhar Dudayev, 
although the Chechen leaders have not received any official 
proposals," says the statement. 
  The Chechen authorities believe that the actual plans of the 
Russian leaders boil down to "backstage contacts between 
Russia's high-ranking officials and dubious figures, who have 
compromised themselves by anti-democratic actions in the Chechen 
Republic," says the document. 

</TEXT>

