  [Text] There was a new provocation yesterday by fanatic 
Islamists against the Ecumenical Patriarchate at Fanari, 
Istanbul, on the eve of the conquest of Constantinople. An 
Islamic organization placed three powerful time-bomb devices, 
which fortunately were discovered in time and dismantled. The 
Greek Government reacted strongly through its spokesman. 
  Commenting on the placement of the three bombs at the 
Ecumenical Patriarchate and Ankara's claims about the so-called 
training of PKK [Workers Party of Kurdistan] members in Greece, 
Government Spokesman Evangelos Venizelos today said that the 
Greek Government is following the continuing Turkish tension and 
provocations with self-restraint. Especially on the latter 
issue, Venizelos stressed that Turkey's claims are close to 
being ridiculous, and called on the Turkish Government to stop 
exporting, has he put it, its political problems and respect the 
rules of Western civilization and international law. 
  New Democracy Chairman Miltiadhis Evert, who is touring 
Pieria, said that he does not consider the planting of bombs at 
the Ecumenical Patriarchate a serious issue, but described the 
statement by the Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman that Greece 
is training PKK members as suspicious. 
  Political Spring Chairman Andonios Samaras today said that 
the Turkish Government has an obligation to take all necessary 
measures for the protection of the Orthodox Ecumenical 
Patriarchate at Fanari. The knowledge that the Orthodoxy's 
unity is symbolized by the Ecumenical Patriarchate leads to 
extremist statements, along with the Kurdish issue which is 
dividing Turkey, Samaras stressed. 

