<H3> <TI>   Death Threats Against Human Rights Ombudsman, Legislator </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Death Threats Against Human Rights Ombudsman, Legislator </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Domingo Monterrosa Command </H4>

<F P=102> PA1006012894 San Salvador Canal Doce Television in Spanish 
0300 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1006012894 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Canal Doce Television </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Up-to-Date" newscast] </F>
  [Text] It was reported this afternoon that a clandestine 
group -- the self-proclaimed Domingo Monterrosa Command -- has 
issued a death threat against Human Rights Ombudsman Carlos 
Mauricio Molina. Molina, however, denied that he himself 
received the death threat, but he did not rule out the 
possibility that such a threat had indeed been made. According 
to news agencies reports, Molina was given 48 hours to leave the 
country, or he will be executed. 
  [Begin Molina recording] I cannot rule out the possibility 
that the threat, which was uttered by people who oppose peace 
and the country's stability, might be serious. [end recording] 
  Molina added that despite the threat, he is willing to 
remain 
in his post, because he has made a pledge to the people and 
intends to fulfill it. He also said he will open an 
investigation to identify the individuals behind the threats -- 
individuals he said should be considered enemies of peace. 
  [Begin Molina recording] The threats against several Jesuits 
do not contribute to the peace process whatsoever. Instead, 
each voice that calls for violence undermines the present trend 
toward peace. [end recording] 
  A communique signed by the Domingo Monterrosa Command and 
reported by various news agencies also contains death against 
the attorney general, the president of the Judiciary Council, 
Jesuit priests, and Luis Gomez Zarate for his criticism of the 
Supreme Electoral Tribunal. 

</TEXT>

