<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   8 June 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> NEAR EAST/SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> ALGERIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Islamic Party Joins in `Combing' Operations Against FIS </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Islamic Party Joins in `Combing' Operations Against FIS </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0906095094 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 8 Jun 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM0906095094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "An Islamic Party Takes Up Arms </F>
Against the Salvation Front"] 
  [Text] Algiers, AL-HAYAH -- Some members of the Algerian 
Transitional National Council members are trying to collect 
signatures on a petition calling for the release of the Islamic 
Salvation Front [FIS] leaders and an end to the state of 
emergency. The deputies trying to promote the petition say that 
the aim is to "support dialogue and national reconciliation." 
AL-HAYAH has learned that the party most opposed to that 
petition is the Islamic "Jihad and Unity Front" which is 
represented in the National Council by Nouari Bousnan (aged 41) 
and Kerghali Saeed (40). Sources close to that front have told 
AL-HAYAH that its leader has formed an armed battalion for 
combating "terrorism" (the word used by the authorities to 
describe the Salvation Front) in the province of El Bouira (120 
km east of the capital), active in Rabta mountains and in 
Boufadil [as transliterated] in the hills of the Kadiria 
District. The same sources confirm that the security forces 
have reinforced that battalion with some soldiers and that the 
initial results of the combing operations "have been 
encouraging." According to Algerian observers, this is the 
first time an Islamic party has participated in military 
operations alongside the Algerian security forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

