<F P=106> [Jad al-Akhawi dispatch from Jba', southern Lebanon] </F>
  [Excerpts] Here in the town of Jba' in Iqlim al-Tuffah the 
inhabitants are cautious. From time to time they hear the 
sounds of bombs or of Israeli reconnaissance planes, which 
usually precede air raids. This is when they rush to shelters 
and safe rooms. [passage omitted] 
  It has been learned that Lebanese Prime Minister Rafiq 
al-Hariri and Hizballah Secretary General Hasan Nasrallah have 
held a telephone conversation in which the need for containing 
the situation and depriving Israel of any pretexts to perpetrate 
new acts of aggression was stressed. It was also learned that 
similar contacts were held between Syrian officials and the 
Hizballah leadership. 
  But, according to fundamentalist sources, the resistance 
will 
continue its operations and a response to the raid near 
Ba'labakk last week must be expected. The sources said the 
visit to Lebanon by Iranian envoy Kazem Khonsari and his 
meetings with Lebanese officials and with resistance leaders 
came as support for the resistance, not to ask it to calm the 
situation and refrain from reacting, as the Lebanese papers 
reported today. 

</TEXT>

